04099nam a22005055i 9780226061405DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013011347  a97802260614057 a10.7208/97802260614052doi  a(DE-B1597)522660  a(OCoLC)855505490  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aE216b.W29 2013 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a973.31 aWarner, William B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProtocols of Liberty :bCommunication Innovation and the American Revolution /cWilliam B. Warner. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b13 halftones, 14 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Communication and The American Crisis -- t1. The Invention of the Boston Committee of Correspondence and the Popular Declaration -- t2. The Protocols of the Declarations and the Eclipse of Royal Power in Massachusetts in 1773 -- t3. The Post and Newspaper in British America: A Communication System in Crisis -- t4. The Whig Network Scales Up: Inflecting the Crisis from Williamsburg -- t5. “A Chain of Freedom Has Been Formed”: The First Continental Congress Develops into the Hub of an Intercolonial Network -- t6. The Panorama of the Declaration -- tConclusion: The American Revolution as a Gift -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe fledgling United States fought a war to achieve independence from Britain, but as John Adams said, the real revolution occurred “in the minds and hearts of the people” before the armed conflict ever began. Putting the practices of communication at the center of this intellectual revolution, Protocols of Liberty shows how American patriots—the Whigs—used new forms of communication to challenge British authority before any shots were fired at Lexington and Concord. To understand the triumph of the Whigs over the Brit-friendly Tories, William B. Warner argues that it is essential to understand the communication systems that shaped pre-Revolution events in the background. He explains the shift in power by tracing the invention of a new political agency, the Committee of Correspondence; the development of a new genre for political expression, the popular declaration; and the emergence of networks for collective political action, with the Continental Congress at its center. From the establishment of town meetings to the creation of a new postal system and, finally, the Declaration of Independence, Protocols of Liberty reveals that communication innovations contributed decisively to nation-building and continued to be key tools in later American political movements, like abolition and women’s suffrage, to oppose local custom and state law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCommunication in politicszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226061405423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226061405.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles